<span class="displaytext"><center><strong>massachusetts during (candidate last)'s term was marked by economic stagnation</strong></center> <p><strong>massachusetts unemployment rate under (candidate last) administration dropped from 5.7% in january 2003 to 5.3% in january 2007, a drop of only 7.02%, which was well below the national reduction of 20.69%.</strong> (u.s. department of labor, bureau of labor statistics, "labor force statistics from the current population survey: unemployment rate," http://data.bls.gov, accessed 7/19/07) </p><p><strong>at end of (candidate last)'s term, unemployment in massachusetts (5.3%) was higher than national unemployment rate of 4.5%. </strong>(massachusetts executive office of labor and workforce development, labor force and unemployment data 2002-2007, http://lmi2.detma.org/lmi/lmi_lur_a.asp, accessed 6/29/07) </p><p><strong>massachusetts under (candidate last) ranked 41st in job growth, "and despite the growth in jobs, the [state department of workforce development] reported that there are 124,100 fewer jobs than before the state's prerecession peak in february 2001." </strong>("campaign ad watch," the boston globe, 8/10/2006; pam belluck, "(candidate last) candidacy puts massachusetts economy in spotlight," the new york times, 3/16/07) </p><p><strong>· (candidate last) spokesman eric fehrnstrom: "'did we recover all the jobs that were lost? no."</strong> (pam belluck, "(candidate last) candidacy puts massachusetts economy in spotlight," the new york times, 3/16/07) </p><p><strong>formal payroll employment in 2006 was 16,000 (0.5%) below its average level in 2002, the third lowest in the nation, and manufacturing payroll employment declined by more than 14% from 2002 to 2006. </strong>(andrew sum and joseph mclaughlin, "(candidate last)'s economic record," the boston globe, 7/29/07) </p><div align="center"><strong>(candidate last) michigan leadership team members voted for largest tax increase in state history</strong></div> <p><strong>two members of (candidate full)'s michigan leadership team voted for recent sales and income tax increases.</strong> "among the very few (PARTY NAME)s who voted for the largest tax increases in michigan's history this week: two endorsers of ex-ma gov. (candidate full). they are: state sen. valde garcia, a member of (candidate last)'s mid-michigan leadership team, and state sen. ron jelinek, a member of (candidate last)'s west michigan leadership team …michigan's 11.5 percent income tax hike and its sales tax extension will almost certainly be the subject of a question or two." (marc ambinder, "michigan tax hike could sting (candidate last) in michigan," the atlantic's "marc ambinder" blog, http://marcambinder.theatlantic.com/archives/2007/10/michigan_tax_hike_could_sting.php#more, 10/4/07)</p></span>



